# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: color-grading
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:color-grading/480i] It originated from the need for a standard to digitize analog 525-line TV (defined in BT.601) and is now used for digital TV broadcasts and home appliances such as game consoles and DVD disc players.
[src:color-grading/480i] The *480* identifies a vertical resolution of 480 lines, and the *i* identifies it as an interlaced resolution.
[src:color-grading/480i] The field rate, which is 60 Hz (or 59.94 Hz when used with NTSC color), is sometimes included when identifying the video mode, i.e.
[src:color-grading/480i] **480i60**; another notation, endorsed by both the International Telecommunication Union in BT.601 and SMPTE in SMPTE 259M, includes the frame rate, as in **480i/30**.
[src:color-grading/480i] Although related, it should not be confused with the analog "525 lines" resolution, mandated by CCIR Systems M and J and usually paired with NTSC color.
[src:color-grading/480i] This association explains why 480i is sometimes inaccurately called "NTSC", even though NTSC only exists in the analog domain.
[src:color-grading/480i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines and the other contains the even ones.
[src:color-grading/480i] By convention an NTSC video frame is considered to start with an even field followed by an odd field.
[src:color-grading/480i] This has the effect of placing a half line of video at the end of the even (first) field and the beginning of the odd (second field).
[src:color-grading/480i] Thus the line numbers correspond to the real lines of the video frame.
[src:color-grading/480i] The NTSC convention solved this confusion.
[src:color-grading/480i] The field rate (not the frame rate) is usually (60/1.001) = 59.94 hertz for color TV and is often incorrectly rounded up to 60 Hz.
[src:color-grading/480i] There are several conventions for written shorthands for the combination of resolution and rate: **480i60**, **480i/30** (EBU/SMPTE always use frame rate to specify interlaced formats) and **480/60i**.
[src:color-grading/480i] 480i is usually used in countries that conventionally use NTSC (most of the Americas and Japan), because the 525 transmitted lines at 60 hertz of analogue NTSC contain 480 visible ones.
[src:color-grading/480i] In each case of the use of the ‘60’ terminology, it is merely shorthand for 59.94, to differentiate it from 30 (29.97) or 24 (23.976).
[src:color-grading/480i] Color information is stored using the YCbCr color space (different from NTSC that used YIQ) with 4:2:2 sampling (also different from NTSC) and following Rec.
[src:color-grading/480i] 480i can be transported by all major digital television formats (ATSC, DVB and ISDB) and on DVD.
[src:color-grading/576i] The *576* identifies a vertical resolution of 576 lines, and the *i* identifies it as an interlaced resolution.
[src:color-grading/576i] The field rate, which is 50 Hz, is sometimes included when identifying the video mode, i.e.
[src:color-grading/576i] **576i50**; another notation, endorsed by both the International Telecommunication Union in BT.601 and SMPTE in SMPTE 259M, includes the frame rate, as in **576i/25**.
[src:color-grading/576i] In analogue television, the full raster uses 625 lines, with 49 lines having no image content to allow time for cathode ray tube circuits to retrace for the next frame (see Vertical blanking interval).
[src:color-grading/576i] These non-displayed lines can be used to transmit teletext or other services.
[src:color-grading/576i] In the digital domain, only the visible 576 lines are considered.
[src:color-grading/576i] Analogue television signals have no pixels; they are continuous along rastered scan lines, but limited by the available bandwidth.
[src:color-grading/576i] The maximal baseband bandwidth is around 6 MHz which, according to the sampling theorem, translates to about 720 pixels.
[src:color-grading/576i] This value is enough to capture all the original information present.
[src:color-grading/576i] In digital applications, the number of pixels per line is an arbitrary choice.
[src:color-grading/576i] Values above about 500 pixels per line are enough for a perceived quality equivalent to analogue free-to-air television; DVB-T, DVD and DV allow better values such as 704 or 720 (matching the maximum theoretical resolution of the original analogue system).
[src:color-grading/576i] Colour information is stored using the YCbCr colour space (regardless of the original PAL or SECAM colour system) with 4:2:2 sampling and following Rec.
[src:color-grading/576i] Originally used for conversion of analogue sources in TV studios, this resolution was adopted into digital broadcasting or home use.
[src:color-grading/576i] The 576i video format can be transported by major digital television formats, ATSC, DVB and ISDB, and on DVD, and it supports aspect ratios of standard 4:3 and anamorphic 16:9.
[src:color-grading/576i] When 576i is used to transmit content that was originally composed of 25 full progressive frames per second (576p25 or 576p/25), the odd field of the frame is transmitted first (this is the opposite to 480i).
[src:color-grading/576i] Systems which recover progressive frames or transcode video should ensure that this field order is obeyed, otherwise the recovered frame will consist of a field from one frame and a field from an adjacent frame, resulting in 'comb' interlacing artifacts.
[src:color-grading/576i] Such progressive content can be marked using encoding flags, for example in DVDs or other MPEG2 based media.
[src:color-grading/576i] Motion pictures shot on film are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:color-grading/576i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:color-grading/576i] This increase in speed also increases the pitch of the audio by a little less than 71 cents.
[src:color-grading/576i] Digital conversion methods can correct for this increased speed and play the video back at its correct speed and pitch, at the expense of a decreased audio sample rate.
[src:color-grading/576i] Some movie enthusiasts may prefer PAL over NTSC despite this increased speed, because the latter results in stutter, a visual distortion not present in sped-up PAL video, where different frames last for uneven amounts of time.
[src:color-grading/576i] This is generally not an issue on modern upconverting DVD players and personal computers, as they play back 23.976023976 fps video at its native frame rate.
[src:color-grading/576i] Another method of converting 24 fps footage to 25 fps is the Euro pulldown, where every frame of the original footage is distributed into two fields, except every 12th frame which lasts for three fields.
[src:color-grading/576i] This preserves the pitch and sample rate of the audio, and the higher resolution of PAL video compared to NTSC, at the expense of more stuttery motion.
[src:color-grading/576i] Yet another method is frame blending, which preserves smooth motion but leaves ghosting artifacts, although it has been criticized by some as looking amateurish.
[src:color-grading/576i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:color-grading/576i] This method reduces the typical DVD sample rate of 48000 Hz to 46080 Hz.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] "**Above-the-line**" refers to the list of individuals who guide and influence the creative direction, process, and voice of a given narrative in a film and related expenditures.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] These roles include but are not limited to the screenwriter, producer, director, and principal cast.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] Often, the term is used for matters related to the film's production budget.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] Above-the-line expenditures reflect the expected line item compensation for an official above-the-line member's role in a given film project.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] These expenditures are usually set, negotiated, spent and/or promised before principal photography begins.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] They include rights to secure the material on which the screenplay is based, production rights to the screenplay, compensation for the screenwriter, producer, director, principal actors and other cost-related line items such as assistants for the producers, director or actors.
[src:color-grading/above-the-line-filmmaking] The distinction originates from the early studio days when the budget top-sheet would literally have a line separating the *above-the-line* and *below-the-line* costs.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coaches need to have a "talent...for reading people, all their utterances and body language." Acting coaches have been called "people whisperers", a reference to "horse whisperers" who help to train animals.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coaches also "...help [drama] students audition for college".
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coach and actor Woodell-Mascall is "...skilled at zeroing in on what young actors need to do to improve their performance." Woodell-Mascall tells one student actor to "...really think about who [the character] is and what she's feeling.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] She provides constructive criticism to students.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Woodell-Mascall has helped students to get into drama programs at schools "...including NYU, Juilliard, Rutgers and UCLA".
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Some acting coaches provide students with a DVD or SD card recording of their acting, for the student to review their progress.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Major acting coaches include: Tad Danielewski, Larry Moss, Ivana Chubbuck, Michelle Danner, Geoff Colman, Terry Schreiber, David Mamet, Lee Strasberg, Michael Woolson, Stella Adler, Chambers Stevens, Sanford Meisner, Paula Strasberg.and Hermann Killmeyer.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coaches may be freelancers who are hired for an hourly or daily rate, or they may be hired on a longer-term basis by a film studio, production company or theatre company.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Some acting coaches have developed their own unique methods and founded their own acting schools.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coaches' income varies a great deal from one coach to another.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] For example, an acting coach providing training to a community theatre troupe or a high school musical earns much less than an acting coach training top Hollywood celebrities.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting classes are often provided in person; however, with the widespread availability of high-speed Internet, some coaches offer mentoring online over Skype or other video linkups.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Acting coaches may offer private coaching, group sessions or a combination of both.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] In some cases, acting coaches are hired to train singers in acting skills.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Popular music singers may need to learn acting skills for their live concert shows, which sometimes include staged sequences, and for performing in music videos.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] For example, Goth-rocker Amy Lee was provided with an acting coach by her record label.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] In Classical music, singers performing staged operas may get help from an acting coach to prepare them for their roles.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Sometimes CEOs and other leaders hire acting coaches to help them improve their performance of speeches and other general communications activities.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] While most acting coaches mentor actors, some also coach directors on how to improve their direction of actors.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] Some acting coaches offer introductions to the acting industry, to help new actors learn about auditions, the casting process, the role of agents, key acting terminology (e.g., "callback" auditions), and about important industry organizations.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] In the television and film industry, in 2018, some production companies are hiring an "intimacy coordinator" to ensure that actors and actresses' sexual consent is obtained before shooting romantic scenes and simulated sex scenes.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] To address concerns about the "vulnerability...and the massive power balance that can happen when a powerful showrunner or director asks an actress or actor...to get naked and simulate sex for the camera", HBO hires an intimacy coordinator for these scenes.
[src:color-grading/acting-coach] The intimacy coordinator is a mix of an acting coach (who makes sure that scenes look realistic) and an advocate for actors and actresses who ensures that the onscreen performers' boundaries are respected and that their physical and emotional comfort is protected.
[src:color-grading/actor] An **actor** (masculine/gender-neutral), or **actress** (feminine), is a person who portrays a character in a production.
[src:color-grading/actor] The actor performs "in the flesh" in the traditional medium of the theatre or in modern media such as film, radio, and television.
[src:color-grading/actor] The analogous Greek term is ὑποκριτής (*hupokritḗs*), literally "one who answers".
[src:color-grading/actor] The actor's interpretation of a role—the art of acting pertains to the role played, whether based on a real person or fictional character.
[src:color-grading/actor] This can also be considered an "actor's role", which was called this due to scrolls being used in the theaters.
[src:color-grading/actor] Interpretation occurs even when the actor is "playing themselves", as in some forms of experimental performance art.
[src:color-grading/actor] Formerly, in ancient Greece and the medieval world, and in England at the time of William Shakespeare, only men could become actors, and women's roles were generally played by men or boys.
[src:color-grading/actor] While Ancient Rome did allow female stage performers, only a small minority of them were given speaking parts.
[src:color-grading/actor] After the English Restoration of 1660, women began to appear onstage in England.
[src:color-grading/actor] In modern times, particularly in pantomime and some operas, women occasionally play the roles of boys or young men.
[src:color-grading/actor] While the word *actor* has existed for much of the history of English language, as to mean "one who does something", it was not used to refer to one who performs in theatre until the 16th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] The profession of acting possesses a significant amount of terminology, some of which is historically or contemporaneously contentious.
[src:color-grading/actor] This includes the term *actress* and less common *player*.
[src:color-grading/actor] According to the *OED*, the earliest recorded occurrence of the term "actress" in reference to stage performance came in 1608 in the anonymous play *Famelie of Love*.
[src:color-grading/actor] Seventeenth-century English writers sometimes used the forms "actoress" or "actoresse" to refer to a female appearing on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the 19th century, many people viewed women in acting negatively, as actresses were often courtesans; females on stage had become associated with promiscuity.
[src:color-grading/actor] Despite such prejudices, the 19th century also saw early female stage "stars", most notably Sarah Bernhardt.
[src:color-grading/actor] After 1660, when women first started to appear on stage regularly in England, the terms *actor* or *actress* initially applied interchangeably to female performers, but later, influenced by the French *actrice*, *actress* became the common term for women in theater and film.
[src:color-grading/actor] The etymology derives from *actor* with *-ess* added.
[src:color-grading/actor] When referring to groups of performers of both sexes, *actors* is preferred.
[src:color-grading/actor] Within the acting profession, the re-adoption of "actor" as a gender-neutral term dates to the post-war period of the 1950s and '60s, when the contributions of women to cultural life in general came under scrutiny.
[src:color-grading/actor] When *The Observer* and *The Guardian* published their new joint style-guide in 2010, it stated "Use ['actor'] for both male and female actors; do not use actress except when in name of award, e.g.
[src:color-grading/actor] I'm an actor – I can play anything." The UK performers' trade-union Equity has no policy on the use of "actor" or "actress".
[src:color-grading/actor] An Equity spokesperson said that the union does not believe that there is a consensus on the matter and stated that the "... subject divides the profession".
[src:color-grading/actor] In 2009, the *Los Angeles Times* stated that "Actress" remains the common term used in major acting awards given to female recipients (e.g., Academy Award for Best Actress).
[src:color-grading/actor] With regard to the cinema of the United States, the gender-neutral term "player" was common in the silent film era and the early days of the Motion Picture Production Code, but in the 2000s in a film context, it is generally deemed archaic.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, "player" remains in use in the theatre, often incorporated into the name of a theatre group or company, such as the American Players, the East West Players, etc.
[src:color-grading/actor] Also, actors in improvisational theatre may be referred to as "players".
[src:color-grading/actor] Before Thespis' act, Grecian stories were only expressed in song, dance, and in third person narrative.
[src:color-grading/actor] In honor of Thespis, actors are commonly called *Thespians*.
[src:color-grading/actor] The exclusively male actors in the theatre of ancient Greece performed in three types of drama: tragedy, comedy, and the satyr play.
[src:color-grading/actor] This developed and expanded considerably under the Romans.
[src:color-grading/actor] The theatre of ancient Rome was a thriving and diverse art form, ranging from festival performances of street theatre, nude dancing, and acrobatics, to the staging of situation comedies, to high-style, verbally elaborate tragedies.
[src:color-grading/actor] As the Western Roman Empire fell into decay through the 4th and 5th centuries, the seat of Roman power was moved eastward to Constantinople.
[src:color-grading/actor] Records show that mime, pantomime, scenes or recitations from tragedies and comedies, dances, and other entertainments were very popular.
[src:color-grading/actor] From the 5th century, Western Europe was plunged into a period of general disorder.
[src:color-grading/actor] Small nomadic bands of actors traveled around Europe throughout the period, performing wherever they could find an audience; there is no evidence that they produced anything but crude scenes.
[src:color-grading/actor] Traditionally, actors were not of high status; therefore, in the Early Middle Ages, traveling acting troupes were often viewed with distrust.
[src:color-grading/actor] Early Middle Ages actors were denounced by the Church during the Dark Ages, as they were viewed as dangerous, immoral, and pagan.
[src:color-grading/actor] In many parts of Europe, traditional beliefs of the region and time meant actors could not receive a Christian burial.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the Early Middle Ages, churches in Europe began staging dramatized versions of biblical events.
[src:color-grading/actor] By the middle of the 11th century, liturgical drama had spread from Russia to Scandinavia to Italy.
[src:color-grading/actor] The Feast of Fools encouraged the development of comedy.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the Late Middle Ages, plays were produced in 127 towns.
[src:color-grading/actor] These vernacular Mystery plays often contained comedy, with actors playing devils, villains, and clowns.
[src:color-grading/actor] The majority of actors in these plays were drawn from the local population.
[src:color-grading/actor] Amateur performers in England were exclusively male, but other countries had female performers.
[src:color-grading/actor] There were several secular plays staged in the Middle Ages, the earliest of which is *The Play of the Greenwood* by Adam de la Halle in 1276.
[src:color-grading/actor] It contains satirical scenes and folk material such as faeries and other supernatural occurrences.
[src:color-grading/actor] Farces also rose in popularity after the 13th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] At the end of the Late Middle Ages, professional actors began to appear in England and Europe.
[src:color-grading/actor] Richard III and Henry VII both maintained small companies of professional actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] Beginning in the mid-16th century, Commedia dell'arte troupes performed lively improvisational playlets across Europe for centuries.
[src:color-grading/actor] Commedia dell'arte was an actor-centred theatre, requiring little scenery and very few props.
[src:color-grading/actor] Plays were loose frameworks that provided situations, complications, and the outcome of the action, around which the actors improvised.
[src:color-grading/actor] A troupe typically consisted of 13 to 14 members.
[src:color-grading/actor] Most actors were paid a share of the play's profits roughly equivalent to the sizes of their roles.
[src:color-grading/actor] Renaissance theatre derived from several medieval theatre traditions, such as the mystery plays, "morality plays", and the "university drama" that attempted to recreate Athenian tragedy.
[src:color-grading/actor] The Italian tradition of Commedia dell'arte, as well as the elaborate masques frequently presented at court, also contributed to the shaping of public theatre.
[src:color-grading/actor] Since before the reign of Elizabeth I, companies of players were attached to the households of leading aristocrats and performed seasonally in various locations.
[src:color-grading/actor] These became the foundation for the professional players that performed on the Elizabethan stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] The development of the theatre and opportunities for acting ceased when Puritan opposition to the stage banned the performance of all plays within London.
[src:color-grading/actor] The re-opening of the theatres in 1660 signalled a renaissance of English drama.
[src:color-grading/actor] English comedies written and performed in the Restoration period from 1660 to 1710 are collectively called "Restoration comedy".
[src:color-grading/actor] Restoration comedy is notorious for its sexual explicitness.
[src:color-grading/actor] At this point, women were allowed for the first time to appear on the English stage, exclusively in female roles.
[src:color-grading/actor] This period saw the introduction of the first professional actresses and the rise of the first celebrity actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the 19th century the negative reputation of actors was largely reversed, and acting became an honored, popular profession and art.
[src:color-grading/actor] The rise of the actor as celebrity provided the transition, as audiences flocked to their favorite "stars".
[src:color-grading/actor] A new role emerged for the actor-managers, who formed their own companies and controlled the actors, the productions, and the financing.
[src:color-grading/actor] When successful, they built up a permanent clientele that flocked to their productions.
[src:color-grading/actor] They could enlarge their audience by going on tour across the country, performing a repertoire of well-known plays, such as those by Shakespeare.
[src:color-grading/actor] The newspapers, private clubs, pubs, and coffee shops rang with lively debates evaluating the relative merits of the stars and the productions.
[src:color-grading/actor] Henry Irving (1838–1905) was the most successful of the British actor-managers.
[src:color-grading/actor] Irving was renowned for his Shakespearean roles, and for such innovations as turning out the house lights so that attention could focus more on the stage and less on the audience.
[src:color-grading/actor] His company toured across Britain, as well as Europe and the United States, demonstrating the power of star actors and celebrated roles to attract enthusiastic audiences.
[src:color-grading/actor] His knighthood in 1895 indicated full acceptance into the higher circles of British society.
[src:color-grading/actor] By the early 20th century, the economics of large-scale productions displaced the actor-manager model.
[src:color-grading/actor] It was too hard to find people who combined a genius at acting as well as management, so specialization divided the roles as stage managers and later theatre directors emerged.
[src:color-grading/actor] Financially, much larger capital was required to operate out of a major city.
[src:color-grading/actor] The solution was corporate ownership of chains of theatres, such as by the Theatrical Syndicate, Edward Laurillard, and especially The Shubert Organization.
[src:color-grading/actor] By catering to tourists, theaters in large cities increasingly favored long runs of highly popular plays, especially musicals.
[src:color-grading/actor] Big name stars became even more essential.
[src:color-grading/actor] Having an actor dress as the opposite sex for comic effect is a long-standing tradition in comic theatre and film.
[src:color-grading/actor] Most of Shakespeare's comedies include instances of overt cross-dressing, such as Francis Flute in *A Midsummer Night's Dream*.
[src:color-grading/actor] The movie *A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum* stars Jack Gilford dressing as a young bride.
[src:color-grading/actor] Tony Curtis and Jack Lemmon famously posed as women to escape gangsters in the Billy Wilder film *Some Like It Hot*.
[src:color-grading/actor] Cross-dressing for comic effect was a frequently used device in most of the Carry On films.
[src:color-grading/actor] Dustin Hoffman and Robin Williams have each appeared in a hit comedy film (*Tootsie* and *Mrs.
[src:color-grading/actor] Doubtfire*, respectively) in which they played most scenes dressed as a woman.
[src:color-grading/actor] Occasionally, the issue can be complicated, for example, by a woman playing a woman acting as a man—who then pretends to be a woman, such as Julie Andrews in *Victor/Victoria*, or Gwyneth Paltrow in *Shakespeare in Love*.
[src:color-grading/actor] In *It's Pat: The Movie*, film-watchers never learn the gender of the androgynous main characters Pat and Chris (played by Julia Sweeney and Dave Foley).
[src:color-grading/actor] Similarly, in *The Marriage of Figaro*, there is a scene in which Cherubino (a male character portrayed by a woman) dresses up and acts like a woman; the other characters in the scene are aware of a single level of gender role obfuscation, while the audience is aware of two levels.
[src:color-grading/actor] Women playing male roles are uncommon in film, with notable exceptions.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1982, Stina Ekblad played the mysterious Ismael Retzinsky in *Fanny and Alexander*, and Linda Hunt received the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress for playing Billy Kwan in *The Year of Living Dangerously*.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 2007, Cate Blanchett was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress for playing Jude Quinn, a fictionalized representation of Bob Dylan in the 1960s, in *I'm Not There*.
[src:color-grading/actor] A few modern roles are played by a member of the opposite sex to emphasize the gender fluidity of the role.
[src:color-grading/actor] Edna Turnblad in *Hairspray* was played by Divine in the 1988 original film, Harvey Fierstein in the Broadway musical, and John Travolta in the 2007 movie musical.
[src:color-grading/actor] Eddie Redmayne was nominated for an Academy Award for playing Lili Elbe (a trans woman) in 2015's *The Danish Girl*.
[src:color-grading/actor] As non-binary and transgender characters have become more commonplace in media, including film, it has become more common for cisgender actors to play those characters, such as Hilary Swank starring as Brandon Teena in *Boys Don't Cry*.
[src:color-grading/actor] Conversely, transgender actors may play cross-gender roles, especially before public transition, such as Elliot Page playing as Shawna Hawkins in the *Tales of the City* miniseries.
[src:color-grading/actor] Formerly, in some societies, only men could become actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] Women appearing on stage in public have been viewed as controversial, provocative and not respectable, and male actors often played the female roles in plays.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Europe and elsewhere, there have been periods of women being barred from acting or placed in restricted roles.
[src:color-grading/actor] In ancient Greece and ancient Rome and the medieval world, it was considered disgraceful for a woman to go on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Nevertheless, women did perform in Ancient Rome, and again entered the stage in the Commedia dell'arte in Italy in the 16th century; in 1562, Lucrezia Di Siena became the perhaps first professional actress since Ancient Rome.
[src:color-grading/actor] France and Spain also had female actors in the 16th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] In William Shakespeare's England, however, women's roles were generally played by men or boys.
[src:color-grading/actor] In ancient Greece, women were barred from appearing on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] There were only male actors in Ancient Greek theatre, and male actors played the female parts in plays.
[src:color-grading/actor] There have even been speculations as to whether women were allowed to watch plays as members of the audience as well.
[src:color-grading/actor] In contrast to Ancient Greek theatre, Ancient Roman theatre did allow female performers.
[src:color-grading/actor] The profession of acting seemingly died out in late antiquity.
[src:color-grading/actor] During the Middle Ages, a broad spectrum of genres of theatre were performed.
[src:color-grading/actor] These genres included mystery plays, morality plays, farces and masques.
[src:color-grading/actor] The actors performing in the medieval theatre genres were normally not professional actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] Rather, they were amateurs who were temporarily engaged to perform a role in a production staged on a temporary basis during some sort of festivity.
[src:color-grading/actor] The amateurs engaged to perform in religious plays were typically drawn from their sponsoring church congregations, and the common thing was to engage men to perform also the female parts.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, women were not explicitly banned, and there were cases in which women were appointed to play.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1514, for example, women were engaged to perform all the female roles in the Bozen Passion Play in the city of Bolzano.
[src:color-grading/actor] Women in Europe first started to appear on stage professionally during the Renaissance.
[src:color-grading/actor] They first did so in Italy, Spain and France.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the mid-17th century, they started to appear on stage in The Holy German Empire and in The Netherlands.
[src:color-grading/actor] England was late to allow women to appear on stage, but they finally did so in the 1660s.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, it is not known if the Italian actors that performed this play were professional actors, or if they were people temporary engaged to participate in the festivities by staging a play, which would not have been uncommon for women during this time period.
[src:color-grading/actor] A letter from Mantova in 1562 mention an unnamed actress from Rome performing with "Moorish dances".
[src:color-grading/actor] Lucrezia Di Siena, whose name is on an acting contract in Rome from 10 October 1564, has been referred to as the first Italian actress known by name, with Vincenza Armani and Barbara Flaminia as the first primadonnas and the first well-documented actresses in Italy (and Europe).
[src:color-grading/actor] From the 1560s onward, actresses became the norm in Italian theaters, and when Italian theater companies toured abroad, Italian actresses became the first women actors performing in many countries.
[src:color-grading/actor] Women also started to appear on stage outside of Italy during the 16th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] During the Spanish Golden Age theatre (1590–1641), women performed on stage from the very beginning.
[src:color-grading/actor] 1570–1614) became the role model for Carmila Lucinda by Lope de Vega; all of them worked as actresses during the 1590s.
[src:color-grading/actor] In France, women appear to have performed in the travelling theater companies early on during the 16th century, though the exact time the first actress appeared is hard to determine.
[src:color-grading/actor] Prior to the establishment of the first permanent theatre in Paris, the actors of the travelling theatre companies are not well documented regardless of their sex.
[src:color-grading/actor] While professional French actresses were reportedly active in France in the second half of the 16th century, they are seldom mentioned by name and then normally only very briefly.
[src:color-grading/actor] Marie Vernier, known also as **Mlle La Porte**, was the leading lady and co-director of Valleran-Lecomte's theatre company, which performed in Hôtel de Bourgogne in Paris and toured the country and the Spanish Netherlands from a least 1604 onward.
[src:color-grading/actor] Following the Renaissance, the art of theatre spread across Europe also outside of the countries the previously enjoyed Italian or English style theatre.
[src:color-grading/actor] Theatre started to develop independently also in the rest of Europe, that experienced its first native professional actors and theatres in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:color-grading/actor] This also created new attitudes to the issue of women performing on stage, since every country now formed their own opinions in the issue.
[src:color-grading/actor] The outcome was that women actors started to appear one by one in each country; sometimes after a law reform explicitly allowing them to act, and sometimes simply as a matter of slow informal development, when individual theater managers started to employ women.
[src:color-grading/actor] This appeared in different times in different countries.
[src:color-grading/actor] In some countries that had native actors, like the Holy Roman Empire and The Netherlands, this happened earlier.
[src:color-grading/actor] In some countries, like the Nordic countries, Poland and Russia, this happened later, simply because they did not have a native theater with native actors until relatively late in time.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Germany and the Netherlands, women started to perform in the native travelling theatre companies in the mid-17th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first actresses were normally the wives and daughters of the theater managers, and their presence were accepted since they performed in a family company under supervision of a father or husband.
[src:color-grading/actor] Initially they were not allowed to perform in the permanent city theatres, but soon they made their debut there as well.
[src:color-grading/actor] On April 19, 1655, Ariana Nozeman made her debut at the stage of the Schouwberg of Van Kampen in Amsterdam in a play by Jan Jacobsz.
[src:color-grading/actor] Schipper which bore her name 'Onvergelijkelijke Ariana' ('Incomparable Ariana'), and thus became the first woman to play a leading role in a public play in The Dutch Republic.
[src:color-grading/actor] The debut of women on stage in Germany appear to have taken place the same year.
[src:color-grading/actor] In September 1655, "female players" are noted to have been performed in Frankfurt for the first time.
[src:color-grading/actor] Under Magister Velthen and his father-in-law Carl Andreas Paulsen, the first actresses were employed in Germany.
[src:color-grading/actor] Velthens wife Catharina Elisabeth Velten acted with her mother and sister on stage in first in her father's and then in her husband's theater, the Hochdeutsche Hofcomödianten, and after her husband's death, she managed his theater and continued his policy of employing women.
[src:color-grading/actor] England was late in introducing women on the stage compared to the rest of Western Europe.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the first half of the 17th century, women were still not allowed on the English stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] The English audience were first introduced to female actors by visiting foreign theatre companies.
[src:color-grading/actor] The perhaps first actress to perform in England was the Italian actress Angelica Martinelli, a member of a visiting Italian Commedia dell'arte company, who performed in England as early as 1578.
[src:color-grading/actor] The rare occurrence of foreign actresses during visits by foreign theatre companies, however, did not result in an English reform, and there were no professional native English actresses.
[src:color-grading/actor] In November 1629, a French theatre company was allowed to make a guest appearance at the Blackfriars Theatre in London, during which the actresses were "hissed, booed and pippin - pelted from the stage".
[src:color-grading/actor] When an eighteen-year Puritan prohibition of drama was lifted after the English Restoration of 1660, women began to appear on stage in England.
[src:color-grading/actor] Margaret Hughes is often credited as the first professional actress on the English stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] The prohibition against female actors ended during the reign of Charles II in part because he enjoyed watching actresses on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Specifically, Charles II issued letters patent to Thomas Killigrew and William Davenant, granting them the monopoly right to form two London theatre companies to perform "serious" drama, and the letters patent were reissued in 1662 with revisions allowing actresses to perform for the first time.
[src:color-grading/actor] In rest of Europe, the debut of women actors came later.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, this was normally not because of a ban on female actors, as had been the case in Western Europe, but rather because Northern and Eastern Europe came late in establishing a national theater with professional native actors of their own.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Northern and Eastern Europe, foreign actresses appeared onstage decades before there were any native actors of any gender.
[src:color-grading/actor] There was never any ban for women performing on the stage in Sweden, and women appear to have performed on stage as soon as the first foreign theatre companies, that included women members, visited Sweden.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1653, a Dutch theatre company performed at the royal court of queen Christina; this theatre company included female members - Ariana Nozeman, Elisabeth de Baer and Susanna van Lee who are believed to have been the likely first actresses to perform in Sweden.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, Sweden relied on foreign theatre companies for a long time and it took decades after the 1650s until native Swedish actresses appeared.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first national theatre to employ professional native actors, the *Kungliga svenska skådeplatsen* was inaugurated at the Stora Bollhuset in 1737; it is noted to have employed three female actors from the start, one of whom being Beata Sabina Straas.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Russia, the first theatre was founded in Moscow by the Tsar in 1672.
[src:color-grading/actor] This theatre did employ women actors, but all actors were foreigners (mainly German).
[src:color-grading/actor] The following decades, many foreign theater companies, mainly from Italy, France and Germany, were active in Moscow and Saint Petersburg.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, it was not until the 30th August 1756 Decree of the Imperial Theatres that native Russians were, for the first time, recruited to be educated in acting.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Poland-Lithuania, Italian, French and German theatre and opera companies had performed at the royal court since the 16th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first public theatre, the National Theatre, Warsaw, was founded in 1765, and the first pioneering group of native Polish actors were employed and trained to perform there.
[src:color-grading/actor] Women were members of this pioneer acting groupe from the start, and Antonina Prusinowska and Wiktoria Leszczyńska is credited as the first two native female actors in Poland.
[src:color-grading/actor] In some cases, this did not occur until the 19th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] After the independence of Greece in 1830, a great interest in theatre flourished in Greece.
[src:color-grading/actor] Initially amateur theatre, a professional theatre developed, and the first modern permanent theatre in Athens, the Boukoura Theatre, was founded in 1840.
[src:color-grading/actor] In professional theatre, women's roles were initially played by men or by foreign (Italian) actresses.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first Greek actress being Maria Angeliki Tzivitza, who performed in the Boukoura Theatre on 24 November 1840, and retired after two performances.
[src:color-grading/actor] Skoufos, Dimitrios Levidis, Alexandros Rizos Rangavis and Grigoris Kampouroglou founded the Athenian Theatre Committee or Society of Theatre with the intent to educate professional Greek actors in Athens.
[src:color-grading/actor] Male actors were swiftly hired, but it was difficult to find women because the profession was not considered respectable for women.
[src:color-grading/actor] Ekaterina Panayotou signed her contract for the Society of Theatre in Athens on 8 November 1842 and became the first female actor hired, followed by Athena Filipaki, Marigo Defteridi and Marigo Domestini.
[src:color-grading/actor] She has the distinction of being the first professional Greek actress with formal training.
[src:color-grading/actor] In Japan, *onnagata*, or men taking on female roles, were used in *kabuki* theatre when women were banned from performing on stage in the 17th century during the Edo period; this ban ended in the 19th century.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1858, Ichikawa Kumehachi made her debut and became the first actress in kabuki theatre since the ban on female actors in 1629, and thus acting as a profession was reintroduced for women in Japan.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1882, she was accepted as a pupil of Ichikawa Danjūrō IX and took the stage name Ichikawa Masunojō.
[src:color-grading/actor] In China, there were several forms of drama, theater and opera.
[src:color-grading/actor] There were never a full ban on women performing onstage, rather the regulations differed depending on which form of drama was performed on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] In some forms of Chinese drama such as Beijing opera, men traditionally performed all the roles, including female roles, while in Shaoxing opera women often play all roles, including male ones.
[src:color-grading/actor] In India, women as well as male actors performed in the Sanskrit theatre during antiquity.
[src:color-grading/actor] The modern theater was introduced in India as an amateur theatre in the 1850s and became commercial in the 1870s, when the first indigenous Indian actress in modern theater made her debut on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Binodini Dasi began her acting career in 1875 at the age of twelve in the Bengali theatre, a domain traditionally dominated by men, and achieved widespread fame for her portrayals of mythological and historical female characters.
[src:color-grading/actor] Before becoming an actress, she worked as a teacher.
[src:color-grading/actor] From 1861, she was engaged at the Arevelian Tatron (Oriental Theater) and she also toured with the company, such as to İzmir in 1867.
[src:color-grading/actor] After this point, male Armenian actors found competition from Muslim Turkish male actors, while no Muslim Turkish female actor ever performed on stage before Afife Jale in the 1920s.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 1870, the modern theater was founded in Egypt with the foundation of the theater company of the theater pioneer Yaqub Sanu.
[src:color-grading/actor] The modern theater art, imported from the Western world, demanded female actors to play female roles.
[src:color-grading/actor] While Yaqub Sanu was able to acquire indigenous male actors, he experienced great difficulty to engage indigenous Egyptian female actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] In this time period, women in Egypt were normally segregated in harems and veiled in public and it was not accepted for a Muslim woman to engage in acting.
[src:color-grading/actor] Yaqub Sanu was allowed to employ women to act on stage since it was seen as necessary, but he was forced to engage non-Muslim women.
[src:color-grading/actor] He was eventually able to employ two poor Jewish girls: Milia Dayan and her sister.
[src:color-grading/actor] The Dayan sisters are known as the first actresses in the Arab world alongside Miriam Samat, Warda Milan, Mathilde Nagga and the sisters Ibriz Estati and Almaz Estati, all of whom were non-Muslim women.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first Muslim actress did not appear in Egypt and the Arab world until Mounira El Mahdeya in 1915.
[src:color-grading/actor] In modern times, women occasionally play the roles of boys or young men.
[src:color-grading/actor] For example, the stage role of Peter Pan is traditionally played by a woman, as are most principal boys in British pantomime.
[src:color-grading/actor] Opera has several "breeches roles" traditionally sung by women, usually mezzo-sopranos.
[src:color-grading/actor] Examples are Hansel in *Hänsel und Gretel*, Cherubino in *The Marriage of Figaro* and Octavian in *Der Rosenkavalier*.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the 2000s, women playing men in live theatre is particularly common in presentations of older plays, such as Shakespearean works with large numbers of male characters in roles where gender is inconsequential.
[src:color-grading/actor] The profession of acting has always had a large breadth of potential incomes.
[src:color-grading/actor] Some actors in 1600s England earned a comfortable income, with Shakespeare himself likely earning 6 shillings per week during his early acting career, which was a typical wage for a skilled tradesman.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 2024, the median hourly wage for actors in the United States was $23.33 per hour.
[src:color-grading/actor] Many lack benefits such as health insurance, with only 12.7% of SAG-AFTRA members earning enough income to qualify for its health plan.
[src:color-grading/actor] Full-time actors in Britain earned a median of £22,500 in the same year, slightly less than the minimum wage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Despite lower median incomes in the profession, some actors earn exceedingly large incomes.
[src:color-grading/actor] Film actors such as Aamir Khan and Sandra Bullock have earned tens of millions of dollars for single film productions.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the United States, union child actors are paid a daily rate of at least $1,204, although due to their legal status as minors, most or all of the income chiefly goes to the parents or legal guardians.
[src:color-grading/actor] In California, the Coogan Act requires 15% of a child's earnings be placed into a blocked trust account, to be opened when they become a legal adult.
[src:color-grading/actor] Illinois, New York, New Mexico, and Louisiana all have similar requirements.
[src:color-grading/actor] In 2015, *Forbes* reported that "...just 21 of the 100 top-grossing films of 2014 featured a female lead or co-lead, while only 28.1 percent of characters in 100 top-grossing films were female...".
[src:color-grading/actor] "In the U.S., there is an "industry-wide [gap] in salaries of all scales.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors working in theatre, film, television, and radio have to learn specific skills.
[src:color-grading/actor] Techniques that work well in one type of acting may not work well in another type of acting.
[src:color-grading/actor] To act on stage, actors need to learn the stage directions that appear in the script, such as "Stage Left" and "Stage Right".
[src:color-grading/actor] These directions are based on the actor's point of view as they stand on the stage facing the audience.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors also have to learn the meaning of the stage directions "Upstage" (away from the audience) and "Downstage" (towards the audience).
[src:color-grading/actor] Theatre actors need to learn blocking, which is "...where and how an actor moves on the stage during a play".
[src:color-grading/actor] The Director also gives instructions on blocking, such as crossing the stage or picking up and using a prop.
[src:color-grading/actor] Some theater actors need to learn stage combat, which is simulated fighting on stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors may have to simulate hand-to-hand fighting or sword-fighting.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors are coached by fight directors, who help them learn the choreographed sequence of fight actions.
[src:color-grading/actor] From 1894 to the late 1920s, movies were silent films.
[src:color-grading/actor] Silent film actors emphasized body language and facial expression, so that the audience could better understand what an actor was feeling and portraying on screen.
[src:color-grading/actor] Much silent film acting is apt to strike modern-day audiences as simplistic or campy.
[src:color-grading/actor] The melodramatic acting style was in some cases a habit actors transferred from their former stage experience.
[src:color-grading/actor] Vaudeville theatre was an especially popular origin for many American silent film actors.
[src:color-grading/actor] The pervading presence of stage actors in film was the cause of this outburst from director Marshall Neilan in 1917: "The sooner the stage people who have come into pictures get out, the better for the pictures".
[src:color-grading/actor] In other cases, directors such as John Griffith Wray required their actors to deliver larger-than-life expressions for emphasis.
[src:color-grading/actor] As early as 1914, American viewers had begun to make known their preference for greater naturalness on screen.
[src:color-grading/actor] Pioneering film directors in Europe and the United States recognized the different limitations and freedoms of the mediums of stage and screen by the early 1910s.
[src:color-grading/actor] Silent films became less vaudevillian in the mid-1910s, as the differences between stage and screen became apparent.
[src:color-grading/actor] Due to the work of directors such as D W Griffith, cinematography became less stage-like, and the then-revolutionary close-up shot allowed subtle and naturalistic acting.
[src:color-grading/actor] Griffith's company Biograph Studios, became known for its innovative direction and acting, conducted to suit the cinema rather than the stage.
[src:color-grading/actor] Griffith realized that theatrical acting did not look good on film and required his actors and actresses to go through weeks of film acting training.
[src:color-grading/actor] Lillian Gish has been called film's "first true actress" for her work in the period, as she pioneered new film performing techniques, recognizing the crucial differences between stage and screen acting.
[src:color-grading/actor] Directors such as Albert Capellani and Maurice Tourneur began to insist on naturalism in their films.
[src:color-grading/actor] By the mid-1920s many American silent films had adopted a more naturalistic acting style, though not all actors and directors accepted naturalistic, low-key acting straight away; as late as 1927, films featuring expressionistic acting styles, such as *Metropolis*, were still being released.
[src:color-grading/actor] According to Anton Kaes, a silent film scholar from the University of Wisconsin, American silent cinema began to see a shift in acting techniques between 1913 and 1921, influenced by techniques found in German silent film.
[src:color-grading/actor] This is mainly attributed to the influx of emigrants from the Weimar Republic, "including film directors, producers, cameramen, lighting and stage technicians, as well as actors and actresses".
[src:color-grading/actor] Film actors have to learn to get used to and be comfortable with a camera being in front of them.
[src:color-grading/actor] Film actors need to learn to find and stay on their "mark".
[src:color-grading/actor] This is a position on the floor marked with tape.
[src:color-grading/actor] This position is where the lights and camera focus are optimized.
[src:color-grading/actor] Film actors also need to learn how to prepare well and perform well on-screen tests.
[src:color-grading/actor] Screen tests are a filmed audition of part of the script.
[src:color-grading/actor] Unlike theater actors, who develop characters for repeat performances, film actors lack continuity, forcing them to come to all scenes (sometimes shot in reverse of the order in which they ultimately appear) with a fully developed character already.
[src:color-grading/actor] "On a television set, there are typically several cameras angled at the set.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors who are new to on-screen acting can get confused about which camera to look into." TV actors need to learn to use lav mics (Lavaliere microphones).
[src:color-grading/actor] TV actors need to understand the concept of "frame".
[src:color-grading/actor] "The term frame refers to the area that the camera's lens is capturing." Within the acting industry, there are four types of television roles one could land on a show.
[src:color-grading/actor] Each type varies in prominence, frequency of appearance, and pay.
[src:color-grading/actor] The first is known as a *series regular*—the main actors on the show as part of the permanent cast.
[src:color-grading/actor] Actors in *recurring* roles are under contract to appear in multiple episodes of a series.
[src:color-grading/actor] A *co-star* role is a small speaking role that usually only appears in one episode.
[src:color-grading/actor] A *guest star* is a larger role than a *co-star* role, and the character is often the central focus of the episode or integral to the plot.
[src:color-grading/actor] Radio drama is a dramatized, purely acoustic performance, broadcast on radio or published on audio media, such as tape or CD.
[src:color-grading/actor] Radio drama achieved widespread popularity within a decade of its initial development in the 1920s.
[src:color-grading/actor] By the 1940s, it was a leading international popular entertainment.
[src:color-grading/actor] With the advent of television in the 1950s, however, radio drama lost some of its popularity, and in some countries has never regained large audiences.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, recordings of OTR (old-time radio) survive today in the audio archives of collectors and museums, as well as several online sites such as Internet Archive.
[src:color-grading/actor] As of 2011, radio drama has a minimal presence on terrestrial radio in the United States.
[src:color-grading/actor] Much of American radio drama is restricted to rebroadcasts or podcasts of programs from previous decades.
[src:color-grading/actor] However, other nations still have thriving traditions of radio drama.
[src:color-grading/actor] In the United Kingdom, for example, the BBC produces and broadcasts hundreds of new radio plays each year on Radio 3, Radio 4, and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:color-grading/actor] Podcasting has also offered the means of creating new radio dramas, in addition to the distribution of vintage programs.
[src:color-grading/actor] The terms "audio drama" or "audio theatre" are sometimes used synonymously with "radio drama" with one possible distinction: audio drama or audio theatre may not necessarily be intended specifically for broadcast on radio.
[src:color-grading/actor] Audio drama, whether newly produced or OTR classics, can be found on CDs, cassette tapes, podcasts, webcasts, and conventional broadcast radio.
[src:color-grading/actor] Thanks to advances in digital recording and Internet distribution, radio drama is experiencing a revival.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop can edit and compose raster images in multiple layers and supports masks, alpha compositing and several color models.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop uses its own PSD and PSB file formats to support these features.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In addition to raster graphics, Photoshop has limited abilities to edit or render text and vector graphics (especially through clipping path for the latter), as well as 3D graphics and video.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Its feature set can be expanded by plug-ins; programs developed and distributed independently of Photoshop that run inside it and offer new or enhanced features.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop's naming scheme was initially based on version numbers.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] However, in October 2002 (following the introduction of Creative Suite branding), each new version of Photoshop was designated with "**CS**" plus a number; e.g., the eighth major version of Photoshop was **Photoshop CS** and the ninth was **Photoshop CS2**.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS3 through CS6 were also distributed in two different editions: Standard and Extended.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] With the introduction of the Creative Cloud branding in June 2013 (and, in turn, the change of the "**CS**" suffix to "**CC**"), Photoshop's licensing scheme was changed to that of subscription model.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Historically, Photoshop was bundled with additional software such as Adobe ImageReady, Adobe Fireworks, Adobe Bridge, Adobe Device Central and Adobe Camera RAW.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Alongside Photoshop, Adobe also develops and publishes Photoshop Elements, Photoshop Lightroom, Photoshop Express, Photoshop Fix, Adobe Illustrator, and Photoshop Mix.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] As of November 2019, Adobe has also released a full version of Photoshop for the iPad, and while initially limited, Adobe plans to bring more features to Photoshop for iPad.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Collectively, they are branded as "The Adobe Photoshop Family".
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop was developed in 1987 by two brothers, Thomas and John Knoll, who sold the distribution license to Adobe Systems Incorporated in 1988.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Thomas Knoll, a Ph.D. student at the University of Michigan, began writing a program on his Macintosh Plus to display grayscale images on a monochrome display.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This program (at that time called **Display**) caught the attention of his brother John, an Industrial Light & Magic employee, who recommended that Thomas turn it into a full-fledged image editing program.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Thomas took a six-month break from his studies in 1988 to collaborate with his brother on the program.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Thomas renamed the program ImagePro, but the name was already taken.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Later that year, Thomas renamed his program **Photoshop** and worked out a short-term deal with scanner manufacturer Barneyscan to distribute copies of the program with a slide scanner; a "total of about 200 copies of Photoshop were shipped" this way.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] During this time, John traveled to Silicon Valley and gave a demonstration of the program to engineers at Apple Computer and Russell Brown, art director at Adobe.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both showings were successful, and Adobe decided to purchase the license to distribute in September 1988.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] While John worked on plug-ins in California, Thomas remained in Ann Arbor writing code.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] *Photoshop* 1.0 was released on February 19, 1990, for Macintosh exclusively.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Barneyscan version included advanced color editing features that were stripped from the first Adobe shipped version.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The handling of color slowly improved with each release from Adobe and Photoshop quickly became the industry standard in digital color editing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] When Photoshop 1.0 was released, digital retouching on dedicated high-end systems (such as the Scitex) cost around $300 an hour for basic photo retouching.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The list price of Photoshop 1.0 for Macintosh in 1990 was $895.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop was initially only available on Macintosh.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In 1993, Adobe chief architect Seetharaman Narayanan ported Photoshop to Microsoft Windows.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Windows port led to Photoshop reaching a wider mass market audience as Microsoft's global reach expanded within the next few years.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] On March 31, 1995, Adobe purchased the rights for Photoshop from Thomas and John Knoll for $34.5 million so Adobe would no longer need to pay a royalty for each copy sold.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop files have default file extension as .**PSD**, which stands for "**P**hoto**s**hop **D**ocument".
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] A PSD file stores an image with support for all features of Photoshop; these include layers with masks, transparency, text, alpha channels and spot colors, clipping paths, and duotone settings.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This is in contrast to many other file formats (e.g., .JPG or .GIF) that restrict content to provide streamlined, predictable functionality.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] A PSD file has a maximum height and width of 30,000 pixels, and a size limit of two gigabytes.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] From the beginning, Photoshop could save files in other formats, including TIF, JPEG, and GIF.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] These files are smaller than PSD files because they lack the editable features of a PSD file.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] These formats are required to use the file in publications or on the web.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe's discontinued program PageMaker required TIF format.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop can also create and use files with the extension .PSB, which stands for "Photoshop Big" (also known as "large document format").
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] A PSB file extends the PSD file format, increasing the maximum height and width to 300,000 pixels and the size limit to around 4 exabytes.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Because of Photoshop's popularity, PSD files are widely used and supported to some extent by most competing software, including GIMP, Affinity Photo, and Clip Studio Paint.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The .PSD file format can be exported to and from Adobe's other apps, such as Adobe Illustrator, Adobe Premiere Pro, and After Effects.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop functionality can be extended by add-on programs called Photoshop plugins (or plug-ins).
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe creates some, such as Adobe Camera Raw, but most are developed by third-parties.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Some are free and some are commercial software.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Most plugins work with only Photoshop or Photoshop-compatible hosts, but a few can also be run as standalone applications.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] There are various types of plugins, such as filter, export, import, selection, color correction, and automation.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The most popular plugins are the filter plugins (also known as a 8bf plugins), available under the Filter menu in Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Filter plugins can either modify the current image or create content.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Camera Raw (also known as ACR and Camera Raw) is a special plugin, supplied free by Adobe, used primarily to read and process raw image files so that the resulting images can be processed by Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It can also be used from within Adobe Bridge.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop's naming scheme was initially based on version numbers, from early pre-release builds and version 1.0 (February 1990) through version 7.0.1.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe published seven major versions before the October 2003 introduction of version 8.0, which brought the *Creative Suite* branding.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 1.0 was released in February 1990.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2.0 was released in June 1991.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It added support for paths and the CMYK color model.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2.5, released in November 1992, was the first version available for Windows.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 3.0 was released in September 1994 for Mac OS 7.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Windows version came out later in November.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Notably, this was the first version that brought *Layers*.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 4.0 was released in November 1996.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 6.0 was released in September 2000.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 7.0 was released in March 2002.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The first Photoshop CS was commercially released in October 2003 as the eighth major version of Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS increased user control with a reworked file browser augmenting search versatility, sorting and sharing capabilities and the Histogram Palette which monitors changes in the image as they are made to the document.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Match Color was also introduced in CS, which reads color data to achieve a uniform expression throughout a series of pictures.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2, released in May 2005, expanded on its predecessor with a new set of tools and features.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It included an upgraded *spot healing brush*, which is mainly used for handling common photographic problems such as blemishes, red-eye, noise, blurring and lens distortion.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe responded to feedback from the professional media industry by implementing non-destructive editing as well as the producing and modifying of 32-bit high dynamic range (HDR) images, which are optimal for 3D rendering and advanced compositing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] FireWire previews could also be viewed on a monitor via a direct export feature.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2 brought the *vanishing point* and *image warping* tools.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] *Vanishing point* tool makes tedious graphic and photo retouching endeavors much simpler by letting users clone, paint and transform image objects while maintaining visual perspective.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] *Image warping* tool makes it easy to digitally distort an image into a shape by choosing on-demand presets or by dragging control points.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The file browser was upgraded to *Adobe Bridge*, which functioned as a hub for productivity, imagery and creativity, providing multi-view file browsing and smooth cross-product integration across Adobe Creative Suite 2 software.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Bridge also provided access to Adobe Stock Photos, a new stock photography service that offered users one-stop shopping across five elite stock image providers to deliver high-quality, royalty-free images for layout and design.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS2 brought a streamlined interface, making it easier to access features for specific instances.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In CS2 users were also given the ability to create their own custom presets, which was meant to save time and increase productivity.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS3 and CS3 Extended were released in April 2007 to the United States and Canada.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] They were also made available through Adobe's online store and Adobe Authorized Resellers.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both CS3 and CS3 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or feature of Adobe Creative Suite.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Macs and PowerPCs, supporting Windows XP and Windows Vista.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS3 is the first release of Photoshop that will run natively on Macs with Intel processors: previous versions can only run through the translation layer Rosetta, and will not run at all on Macs running Mac OS X 10.7 or later.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS3 improves on features from previous versions of Photoshop and introduces new tools.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] One of the most significant is the streamlined interface which allows increased performance, speed, and efficiency.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] There is also improved support for Camera RAW files which allow users to process images with higher speed and conversion quality.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS3 supports over 150 RAW formats as well as JPEG, TIFF and PDF.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Enhancements were made to the Black and White Conversion, Brightness and Contrast Adjustment and Vanishing Point Module tools.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Black and White adjustment option improves control over manual grayscale conversions with a dialog box similar to that of Channel Mixer.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] There is more control over print options and better management with Adobe Bridge.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Clone Source palette is introduced, adding more options to the clone stamp tool.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Other features include the nondestructive Smart Filters, optimizing graphics for mobile devices, Fill Light and Dust Busting tools.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Compositing is assisted with Photoshop's new Quick Selection and Refine Edge tools and improved image stitching technology.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS3 Extended includes everything in CS3 and additional features.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] There are tools for 3D graphic file formats, video enhancement and animation, and comprehensive image measurement and analysis tools with DICOM file support.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The 3D graphic formats allow 3D content to be incorporated into 2D compositions.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] As for video editing, CS3 supports layers and video formatting so users can edit video files per frame.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS4 and CS4 Extended were released on October 15, 2008.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both CS4 and CS4 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or feature of Adobe Creative Suite.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Mac OS X and PowerPCs, supporting Windows XP and Windows Vista.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS4 features smoother panning and zooming, allowing faster image editing at a high magnification.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The interface is more simplified with its tab-based interface making it cleaner to work with.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS4 features a new 3D engine allowing the conversion of gradient maps to 3D objects, adding depth to layers and text, and getting print-quality output with the new ray-tracing rendering engine.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It supports common 3D formats; the new Adjustment and Mask panels; content-aware scaling (seam carving); fluid canvas rotation and File display options.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The content-aware scaling allows users to intelligently size and scale images, and the canvas rotation tool makes it easier to rotate and edit images from any angle.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe released Photoshop CS4 Extended, which has the features of Adobe Photoshop CS4, plus capabilities for scientific imaging, 3D, motion graphics, accurate image analysis and high-end film and video users.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The faster 3D engine allows users to paint directly on 3D models, wrap 2D images around 3D shapes and animate 3D objects.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] As the successor to Photoshop CS3, Photoshop CS4 is the first x64 edition of Photoshop on consumer computers for Windows.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The color correction tool has also been improved significantly.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS5 was launched on April 12, 2010.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In a video posted on its official Facebook page, the development team revealed the new technologies under development, including three-dimensional brushes and warping tools.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In May 2011, Adobe Creative Suite 5.5 (CS5.5) was released, with new versions of some of the applications.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Its version of Photoshop, 12.1, is identical to the concurrently released update for Photoshop CS5, version 12.0.4, except for support for the new subscription pricing that was introduced with CS5.5.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS5 introduces new tools such as the Content-Aware Fill, Refine Edge, Mixer Brush, Bristle Tips and Puppet Warp.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The community also had a hand in the additions made to CS5 as 30 new features and improvements were included by request.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] These include automatic image straightening, the Rule-of-Thirds cropping tool, color pickup, and saving a 16-bit image as a JPEG.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Another feature includes the Adobe Mini Bridge, which allows for efficient file browsing and management.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS5 Extended includes everything in CS5 plus features in 3D and video editing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] A new materials library was added, providing more options such as Chrome, Glass, and Cork.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The new Shadow Catcher tool can be used to further enhance 3D objects.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] For motion graphics, the tools can be applied to over more than one frame in a video sequence.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS5 and CS5 Extended were made available through Adobe's online store, Adobe Authorized Resellers and Adobe direct sales.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both CS5 and CS5 Extended are offered as either a stand-alone application or a feature of Adobe Creative Suite 5.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Both products are compatible with Intel-based Mac OS X and Windows XP, Windows Vista, and Windows 7.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CS6, released in May 2012, added new creative design tools and provided a redesigned interface with a focus on enhanced performance.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] New features have been added to the Content-Aware tool such as the Content-Aware Patch and Content-Aware Move.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe Photoshop CS6 brought a suite of tools for video editing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Color and exposure adjustments, as well as layers, are among a few things that are featured in this new editor.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Upon completion of editing, the user is presented with a handful of options of exporting into a few popular formats.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS6 brings the "straighten" tool to Photoshop, where a user simply draws a line anywhere on an image, and the canvas will reorient itself so that the line drawn becomes horizontal, and adjusts the media accordingly.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This was created with the intention that users will draw a line parallel to a plane in the image, and reorient the image to that plane to more easily achieve certain perspectives.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS6 allows background saving, which means that while another document is compiling and archiving itself, it is possible to simultaneously edit an image.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CS6 also features a customizable auto-save feature, preventing any work from being lost.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] With version 13.1.3, Adobe dropped support for Windows XP (including Windows XP Professional x64 Edition); thus, the last version that works on Windows XP is 13.0.1.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe also announced that CS6 will be the last suite sold with perpetual licenses in favor of the new Creative Cloud subscriptions, though they will continue to provide OS compatibility support as well as bug fixes and security updates as necessary.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Starting January 9, 2017, CS6 is no longer available for purchase, making a Creative Cloud license the only purchase option going forward.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] No more updates will be available for all CS6 software either.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC (14.0) was launched on June 18, 2013.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] As the next major version after CS6, it is only available as part of a Creative Cloud subscription.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Major features in this version include new Smart Sharpen, Intelligent Upsampling, and Camera Shake Reduction for reducing blur caused by camera shake.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Editable Rounded Rectangles and an update to Adobe Camera Raw (8.0) were also included.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Since the initial launch, Adobe has released two additional feature-bearing updates.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The first, version 14.1, was launched on September 9, 2013.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The major features in this version were Adobe Generator, a Node.js-based platform for creating plug-ins for Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 14.1 shipped with two plug-ins, one to automatically generate image assets based on an extension in the layer name, and another to automatically generate assets for Adobe Edge Reflow.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 14.2 was released on January 15, 2014.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Major features include Perspective Warp, Linked Smart Objects, and 3D Printing support.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CC 2014 features improvements to content-aware tools, two new blur tools (spin blur and path blur) and a new focus mask feature that enables the user to select parts of an image based on whether they are in focus or not.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Other minor improvements have been made, including speed increases for certain tasks.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2015 was released on June 15, 2015.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe added various creative features including Adobe Stock, which is a library of custom stock images.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It also includes and have the ability to have more than one layer style.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] For example, in the older versions of Photoshop, only one shadow could be used for a layer but in CC 2015, up to ten are available.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Other minor features like Export As, which is a form of the Save For Web in CC 2014 were also added.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The updated UI as of November 30, 2015, delivers a cleaner and more consistent look throughout Photoshop, and the user can quickly perform common tasks using a new set of gestures on touch-enabled devices like Microsoft Surface Pro.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] CC 2015 also marks the 25th anniversary of Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2017 was released on November 2, 2016.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It introduced a new template selector when creating new documents, the ability to search for tools, panels and help articles for Photoshop, support for SVG OpenType fonts and other small improvements.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] In December 2016, a minor update was released to include support for the MacBook Pro Touch Bar.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2018 (version 19) was released on October 18, 2017.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It featured an overhaul to the brush organization system, allowing for more properties (such as color and opacity) to be saved per-brush and for brushes to be categorized in folders and sub-folders.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It also added brush stroke smoothing, and over 1000 brushes created by Kyle T.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Webster (following Adobe's acquisition of his website, KyleBrush.com).
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] A Curvature Pen tool, similar to the one in Illustrator, was added, allowing for faster creation of Bézier paths.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop CC 2019 was released on October 15, 2018.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Beginning with Photoshop CC 2019 (version 20.0), the 32-bit version of Windows is no longer supported.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This version Introduced a new tool called Frame Tool to create placeholder frames for images.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It also added multiple undo mode, auto-commitment, and prevented accidental panel moves with lock work-space.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Live blend mode previews are added, allowing for faster scrolling over different blend mode options in the layers panel.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop 2020 was released on November 4, 2019.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 21 has many new and enhanced features like the new object selection tool for better automation of complex selections, new properties panel, enhanced transform warp, new keyboard shortcuts for paint & brush and background image removal option.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It added several improvements to the new content-aware fill and to the new document tab.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Also added were animated GIF support, improved lens blur performance and one-click zoom to a layer's contents.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It introduced new swatches, gradients, patterns, shapes and stylistic sets for OpenType fonts.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] With this version users now can easily convert smart objects to layers and also can adjust 32-bit layers for brightness/contrast and curves.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Presets are now more intuitive to use and easier to organize.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] With the February 2020 update (version 21.1) Photoshop now can iteratively fill multiple areas of an image without having to leave content-aware fill workspace.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This version improved GPU based lens blur quality and provided performance improvements, such as accelerating workflows with smoother panning, zooming and navigation of documents.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 21 was the first version where the iPad version was released.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] With Photoshop on the iPad, combined with the new Cloud PSD file format, a user can save cloud documents and work across Windows, Mac and iPad.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Photoshop on the iPad does not have all the features of the desktop Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe promises to update Photoshop on the iPad at "a much more aggressive pace than it has with its current Creative Cloud apps for the desktop".
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Adobe has provided a timeline for enhancing Photoshop on the iPad to have more of the features of desktop Photoshop.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 21.2 of the desktop version was released in June 2020.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It introduced faster portrait selection, Adobe Camera Raw improvements, auto-activated Adobe Fonts, rotatable patterns, and improved Match Font.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.0.0 was released in October 2020.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.0.1 was released in November 2020.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.1.0 was released in December 2020.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.1.1 was released in January 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.2 was released in February 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.3 was released in March 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This is the first macOS release to run natively on Apple silicon.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.3.1 was released in April 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.1 was released in May 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.2 was released in June 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.4.3 was released in July 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.5 was released in August 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 22.5.1 was released in September 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Final version to include (as Legacy Swatches) a large set of Pantone color books, including Pastels & Neons, and Premium Metallics.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0 was released in October 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] First version to include (as Legacy Swatches) a reduced set of Pantone color books - only CMYK, Metallics and Solid colors.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Content Credentials (Beta) was introduced.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] When enabled, the editing information is captured in a tamper-evident form and resides with the file through successive copy generations.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] It aligns with the C2PA standard on digital provenance across the internet.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0.1 was released in November 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.0.2 was released in November 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.1 was released in December 2021.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.1.1 was released in January 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.2 was released in February 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.3 was released in April 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 23.5 was released in August 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Final version with built-in support for basic Pantone colors - CMYK, Metallics and Solid (as Legacy Swatches).
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Future versions require a separate subscription to access Pantone colors.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.0 was released in October 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] First version without built-in support for Pantone colors.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] All Pantone colors have been removed as of August 16, 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Separate paid subscription now required to access Pantone Connect extension and download color "fandecks".
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.1 was released in December 2022.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 24.7 was released on July 27, 2023.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 25.0 was released in September 2023.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This version added Generative Fill and Generative Expand for commercial use.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] This was the last version where the CPU requirements on the Intel platform were limited to only SSE 4.2 instructions, which meant the x86-64-v2 microarchitecture (Intel Nehalem and newer, AMD Bulldozer and newer).
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Version 26 was released in October 2024.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The CPU requirements on the Intel platform have been increased to support AVX2 instructions, which means the x86-64-v3 microarchitecture (Intel Haswell and newer, AMD Excavator and newer).
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] The Adobe Photoshop family is a group of applications and services made by Adobe for the use of professional image editing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-photoshop] Several features of the Adobe Photoshop family are pixel manipulating, image organizing, photo retouching, and more.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Adobe offered individual products as well as software suites containing several products (such as Adobe Creative Suite or Adobe eLearning Suite) with a perpetual software license.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Adobe first announced the Creative Cloud in October 2011.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Another version of Adobe Creative Suite was released the following year.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] On May 6, 2013, Adobe announced that they would not release new versions of the Creative Suite and that future versions of its software would be available only through the Creative Cloud.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The first new versions made only for the Creative Cloud were released on June 17, 2013.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The Adobe Creative Cloud retains many of the features of Adobe Creative Suite and introduces new features; foremost is the instant availability of upgrades, saving to the cloud, and easier sharing.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] In June 2014, the company announced 14 new versions of the Creative Cloud essential desktop tools, four new mobile apps, and the availability of creative hardware for enterprise, education and photography customers.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The video disc authoring program Adobe Encore and the web-focused bitmap editor Adobe Fireworks were both discontinued by Adobe in 2013, but were still available as downloads via Creative Cloud until May 2019.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The following contains the services found on Creative Cloud.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The change from perpetual licenses to a subscription model was met with significant criticism.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Although Adobe's cloud-based model caused disagreement and uncertainty, and incited annoyance and conflict, a survey by CNET and Jefferies revealed that despite complaints most of its 1.4 million subscribers plan to renew.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Shifting to a subscription-based licensing model using cloud computing, Adobe announced more frequent feature updates to its products and the eschewing of their traditional release cycles.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Customers must pay a monthly subscription fee.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Consequently, if subscribers cancel or stop paying, they will lose access to all or some of the software as well as the ability to open work saved in its proprietary file formats.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Creative Cloud has been described as an example of enshittification.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Although investors applauded the move, many customers reacted negatively.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] This shift has been met with mixed reviews by both corporations and independent designers, with many people expressing their displeasure on the web and through multiple Internet petitions.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Among these was a Change.org petition which reached over 30,000 signatures within a few weeks of the announcement.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Creative Cloud has been criticized for broken file syncing, one of its core features.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] In May 2013 Adobe announced that it was suspending the file-sync desktop preview "for the next couple of weeks".
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Reviewers of Creative Cloud were disappointed with the functionality of the cloud storage and were "far from convinced by Adobe's subscription model".
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Some users were concerned that they would be forced to upgrade their computer hardware when it is no longer supported by the current version of the Creative Cloud software.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Some of their customers experienced a loss of trust in Adobe as a company and an attendant rise in anxiety.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] In May 2014 the service was interrupted for over a day due to a login outage leaving graphics professionals locked out of Creative Cloud.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Adobe apologized for this global Creative Cloud failure.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] When initially asked whether customers would be compensated, the company's Customer Service responded: "We cannot offer compensation for the outage.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] I'm so sorry again for the frustration." Adobe later announced that it would review compensation on "a case by case basis".
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The outage was heavily criticized, as was Adobe's subscription-based licensing model in general.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Online articles began offering examples of replacements for Adobe products, with competing products directly offering alternatives, and launching promotions for dissatisfied Adobe customers.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Although Creative Cloud was expected to curtail the piracy of Photoshop, which is one of the most pirated pieces of software, Creative Cloud was hacked and its applications were made available via unauthorized means a day after it officially launched.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Adobe claimed that the subscription payment plan would make its software more accessible to users who previously pirated it.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] On May 14, 2019, some Creative Cloud users received emails from Adobe stating that licenses to previous versions of Creative Cloud applications had been terminated and that users could face civil action from third parties if they did not update the software on their personal computers.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] A representative from Adobe confirmed the letter's authenticity.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] The situation prompted renewed criticism of Adobe's subscription-only business model.
[src:color-grading/adobe-speedgrade] Adobe users who sign NDAs could be in trouble after Adobe updated its terms of service to force users to share their content with Adobe, a clause that will compromise any NDA.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color grading and color correction are often used synonymously as terms for this process and can include the generation of artistic color effects through creative blending and compositing of different layer masks of the source image.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color grading is generally now performed in a digital process either in a controlled environment such as a color suite, and is usually done in a dim or dark environment.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The earlier photochemical film process, referred to as **color timing**, was performed at a film lab during printing by varying the intensity and color of light used to expose the rephotographed image.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Since, with this process alone, the user was unable to immediately view the outcome of their changes, the use of a Hazeltine color analyzer was common for viewing these modifications in real time.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In the 2000s, with the increase of digital technology, color grading in Hollywood films became more common.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color timing is used in reproducing film elements.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] "Color grading" was originally a lab term for the process of changing color appearance in film reproduction when going to the answer print or release print in the film reproduction chain.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] By the late 2010s, this film grading technique had become known as *color timing* and still involved changing the duration of exposure through different filters during the film development process.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color timing is specified in printer points which represent presets in a lab contact printer where 7 to 12 printer points represent one stop of light.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The number of points per stop varied based upon negative or print stock and different presets at film labs.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In a film production, the creative team would meet with the “lab timer” who would watch a running film and make notes dependent upon the team's directions.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] After the session, the timer would return to the lab and put the film negative on a device (the Hazeltine) which had preview filters with a controlled backlight, picking exact settings of each printer point for each scene.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] These settings were then punched onto a paper tape and fed to the high-speed printer where the negative was exposed through a backlight to a print stock.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Filter settings were changed on the fly to match the printer lights that were on the paper tape.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] For complex work such as visual effects shots, "wedges” running through combinations of filters were sometimes processed to aid the choice of the correct grading.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] This process is used wherever film materials are being reproduced.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] With the advent of television, broadcasters quickly realised the limitations of live television broadcasts and they turned to broadcasting feature films from release prints directly from a telecine.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] This was before 1956 when Ampex introduced the first Quadruplex videotape recorder (VTR) VRX-1000.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Live television shows could also be recorded to film and aired at different times in different time zones by filming a video monitor.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The heart of this system was the *kinescope*, a device for recording a television broadcast to film.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The early telecine hardware was the "film chain" for broadcasting from film and utilized a film projector connected to a video camera.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In a cathode-ray tube (CRT) system, an electron beam is projected at a phosphor-coated envelope, producing a small spot of light.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] This beam is then scanned across a film frame from left to right, capturing the "vertical" frame information.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Horizontal scanning of the frame is then accomplished as the film moves past the CRT's beam.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Once this photon beam passes through the film frame, it encounters a series of dichroic mirrors which separate the image into its primary red, green and blue components.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] From there, each individual beam is reflected onto a photomultiplier tube (PMT) where the photons are converted into an electronic signal to be recorded to tape.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In a charge-coupled device (CCD) telecine, a white light is shone through the exposed film image onto a prism, which separates the image into the three primary colors, red, green and blue.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Each beam of colored light is then projected at a different CCD, one for each color.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The CCD converts the light into an electronic signal, and the telecine electronics modulate these into a video signal that can then be color graded.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Early color correction on Rank Cintel MkIII CRT telecine systems was accomplished by varying the primary gain voltages on each of the three photomultiplier tubes to vary the output of red, green and blue.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Further advancements converted much of the color-processing equipment from analog to digital and then, with the next-generation telecine, the Ursa, the coloring process was completely digital in the 4:2:2 color space.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The Ursa Gold brought about color grading in the full 4:4:4 color space.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color correction control systems started with the Rank Cintel TOPSY (Telecine Operations Programming SYstem) in 1978.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In 1984 Da Vinci Systems introduced their first color corrector, a computer-controlled interface that would manipulate the color voltages on the Rank Cintel MkIII systems.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Since then, technology has improved to give extraordinary power to the digital colorist.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Today there are many companies making color correction control interfaces including Da Vinci Systems and Pandora International.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Some telecines are still in operation in 2018.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Note that some of these functions must be prioritized over others; for example, color grading may be done to ensure that the recorded colors match those of the original scene, whereas other times, the goal may instead be to establish a very artificial stylized look.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color grading is one of the most labour intensive parts of video editing.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Traditionally, color grading was done towards practical goals.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] For example, in the film *Marianne*, grading was used so that night scenes could be filmed more cheaply in daylight.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Secondary color grading was originally used to establish color continuity; however, the trend today is increasingly moving towards creative goals such as improving the aesthetics of an image, establishing stylized looks, and setting the mood of a scene through color.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Due to this trend, some colorists suggest the phrase "color enhancement" over "color correction".
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Primary color grading affects the whole image by providing control over the color density curves of red, green, blue color channels, across the entire frame.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Secondary grading can isolate a range of hue, saturation and brightness values to bring about alterations in hue, saturation and luminance only in that range, allowing the grading of secondary colors, while having a minimal or usually no effect on the remainder of the color spectrum.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Using digital grading, objects and color ranges within a scene can be isolated with precision and adjusted.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color tints can be manipulated and visual treatments pushed to extremes not physically possible with laboratory processing.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] With these advancements, the color grading process has become increasingly similar to well-established digital painting techniques, ushering forth a new era of digital cinematography.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The evolution of digital color grading tools has advanced to the point where the colorist can use geometric shapes (such as mattes or masks in photo software such as Adobe Photoshop) to isolate color adjustments to specific areas of an image.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] These tools can, for example, highlight a wall in the background and color only that wall, leaving the rest of the frame alone, or color everything but that wall.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Subsequent color grading tools (typically software-based) have the ability to use spline-based shapes for even greater control over isolating color adjustments.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Color keying is also used for isolating areas to adjust.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Inside and outside of area-based isolations, digital filtration can be applied to soften, sharpen or mimic the effects of traditional glass photographic filters.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] When trying to isolate a color adjustment on a moving subject, the colorist traditionally would manually move a mask to follow the subject.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In its most simple form, motion tracking software automates this time-consuming process using algorithms to evaluate the motion of a group of pixels.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] These techniques are generally derived from match moving techniques used in special effects and compositing work.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] From 2010, many films, such as *Hot Tub Time Machine* and *Iron Man 2,* began using the complementary colors orange and teal.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The evolution of the telecine device into film scanning allowed the digital information scanned from a film negative to be of sufficient resolution to transfer back to film.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In the early 1990s, Kodak developed the Cineon Film System to capture, manipulate, and record back to film and they called this the “Digital Intermediate”.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In the late 1990s, the films *Pleasantville* and *O Brother, Where Art Thou?* advanced the technology to the point that the creation of a digital intermediate was practical, which greatly expanded the capabilities of the digital telecine colorist to the traditionally-oriented world of feature films.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Since 2010, almost all feature films have gone through the DI process, while manipulation through photochemical processing is rare or used on archival films.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In Hollywood, *O Brother, Where Art Thou?* was the first film to be wholly digitally graded.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The negative was scanned with a Spirit DataCine at 2K resolution, then colors were digitally fine-tuned using a Pandora MegaDef color corrector on a Virtual DataCine.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The process took several weeks, and the resulting digital master was output to film again with a Kodak laser recorder to create a master internegative.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Modern motion picture processing typically uses both digital cameras and digital projectors.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Calibrated devices are most commonly used to maintain a consistent appearance within the workflow.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] In early use, hardware-based systems (da Vinci 2K, Pandora International MegaDEF, etc.) have historically offered better performance but a smaller feature set than software-based systems.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Their real time performance was optimized to particular resolution and bit depths, as opposed to software platforms using standard computer industry hardware that often trade speed for resolution independence, e.g.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Apple's Color (previously Silicon Color Final Touch), ASSIMILATE SCRATCH, Adobe SpeedGrade and SGO Mistika.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] While hardware-based systems always offer real-time performance, some software-based systems need to pre-render as the complexity of the color grading increases.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] On the other hand, software-based systems tend to have more features such as spline-based windows/masks and advanced motion tracking.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The line between hardware and software no longer exists as many software-based color correctors (e.g.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Pablo, Mistika, SCRATCH, Autodesk Lustre, Nucoda Film Master and FilmLight's Baselight) use multi processor workstations and a GPU (graphics processing unit) as a means of hardware acceleration.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] As well, some newer software-based systems use a cluster of multiple parallel GPUs on the one computer system to improve performance at the very high resolutions required for feature film grading. e.g.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Some color grading software like Synthetic Aperture's Color Finesse runs solely as software and will even run on low-end computer systems.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] High-speed RAID arrays are an essential part of the process for all systems.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] Hardware systems are no longer common because of the price/performance of software systems.
[src:color-grading/color-grading] The control panels are placed in a color suite for the colorist to operate the telecine remotely.
